  "prompt": "Is it generally understood that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, it is widely understood that money laundering is illegal. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, in order to make it appear as though it came from legitimate sources. This practice is criminalized in most jurisdictions around the world, and both international and national laws have been established to combat it.\n\nKey aspects of why money laundering is illegal include:\n\n1. **Facilitation of Illegal Activities:** Money laundering often facilitates other serious crimes, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud.\n  \n2. **Undermining Financial Systems:** It can undermine the integrity of financial institutions and destabilize economies by introducing illicit funds into the legitimate financial system.\n\n3. **Tax Evasion:** Money laundering is often associated with tax evasion, depriving governments of revenue that could be used for public services.\n\n4. **Global Cooperation:** International bodies like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) have established guidelines and standards to combat money laundering, and countries around the world have implemented laws to criminalize and prevent it.\n\nIn summary, the illegality of money laundering is a well-established legal principle globally, reflecting its harmful impact on both the economy and society.",
